@Robert Murray-Smith this has me wondering: how little inner/outer diameter thickness at how large of a diameter can you make this, and will that multiply the practical effects?

For example to explain it, keep the cheese wedges the same inner/outer distance, but make them cover a tiny portion of a circle each, say, many yards/meters in diameter. Then, have a similar diameter (inner/outer thickness being small) turbine so there’s not much mass. Sure, a larger diameter has a lot more inertia, and tuning may be more problematic (TBD) than one with blades deeper into the center, but it’d also be easier to manufacture.

Now, for fun: imagine wrapping a grain silo with this. Next thing you know, if this scales nicely, farmers are at minimum self-sufficient for electricity, and that can’t be a bad thing.
